<!-- ============================================ 
  Síntesis de la lección (discusión de cierre)
=================================================  -->
<subsubsection xml:id="lec-representarDatosDeMedidasEnDiagramasDePuntos-sintesis" component="profesor">
  <shorttitle><custom ref="synthesis-leccion-titulo"/></shorttitle>
  <title><custom ref="synthesis-leccion-titulo"/></title>
  <title component="profesor"><nbsp/>(5 mins)</title>

  <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
  <p>Discuss students' observations from the gallery walk.</p>
  <p><q>¿En qué se parecen los diagramas de puntos?</q> (They all show lengths in inches and at least 10 x’s. They all show at least one stack of x’s that is taller.)</p>
  <p><q>¿En qué son diferentes?</q> (They represent lengths of different objects. Some line plots show more or fewer x’s than others. The numbers on the ends of the lines are different. The locations of x’s and how they are spread out are different. On some line plots, each space represents <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> inch. On others, it represents <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> inch.)</p>
  <p><q>¿Por qué los diagramas de puntos tenían escalas diferentes?</q> (Some types of objects are usually longer than others. For example, twigs are usually longer than leaves. Some data include only lengths in half inches. Others include quarters of an inch.)</p>
  <p>Consider asking: <q>¿Qué aprendieron sobre los diagramas de puntos en las últimas lecciones?</q> (They are used to show measurements, including fractions an inch. We can choose the scale of the line plot based on the measurements. We can get some information about the data more easily from a line plot than from a list.)</p>

</subsubsection>



